      the classic ERR_CONNECTION_REFUSED! Don't worry, rithul, this is a rite of passage for every DevOps engineer. 😅
      When you see this in Kubernetes, it usually means one of two things:
      -The Pod isn't ready yet: Kubernetes might still be downloading your image from Docker Hub.
      -Localhost Routing: Depending on how your local Kubernetes is set up (Docker Desktop vs. Minikube), K8s sometimes needs an extra push to map the internal port to your Windows localhost.
      
      Step 1: Check if the Pod is actually running
      Let's make sure your container didn't crash and is actually running inside K8s. Run this in your VS Code terminal:
      kubectl get pods
      
      Step 2: Check the Service
      Let's verify that Kubernetes registered your port 30001. Run:
      kubectl get svc
      
      Step 3: The Guaranteed Fix (Port Forwarding)
      Sometimes Windows and local Kubernetes get confused about localhost. The most reliable way to force the connection to open on your machine is to use Kubernetes Port Forwarding.
      Run this command in your terminal and leave the terminal running (don't close it):
      kubectl port-forward service/employee-v1-service 30001:80
      
      Once you see Forwarding from 127.0.0.1:30001 -> 80, go back to your browser and refresh http://localhost:30001.
